cs.SI, cs.CL, cs.SOC, cs.CYBER, cs.CR 

This paper analyzes a large dataset of Arabic language comments on Twitter related to ISIS, which suggests a focus on social media analysis (cs.SOC) and natural language processing (cs.CL). The paper also explores the relationship between online opinions and the number of foreign fighters joining ISIS, which could fall under the category of cybersecurity (cs.CYBER) or computer crime (cs.CR). Finally, the paper uses time-granularity to link opinions with daily events, which could be related to social media analytics (cs.SI).
